    - target: {fileID: 5502387711208104083, guid: a01cfc34c5d09034dbd62d1a7d2cc505,
        type: 3}
      propertyPath: m_Text
      value: "Storage devices are critical components of modern computer systems.
        They serve the essential function of holding and preserving digital information
        for both short-term and long-term use. While input devices allow users to
        send data into a computer and output devices display the results, storage
        devices ensure that the data and programs we use are safely saved for future
        access, even after the computer is turned off.\n\nUnlike volatile memory,
        such as RAM, which temporarily holds data during active use, storage devices
        are non-volatile, meaning they retain information even when the system is
        powered down. This distinction is vital for keeping files, software, and
        system settings intact over time.\n\nSeveral types of storage devices exist,
        each with unique characteristics and uses:\n\u2022 Hard Disk Drives (HDD):
        Traditional storage devices that use spinning magnetic disks to store data.
        HDDs provide large storage capacity at a relatively low cost but are slower
        than some modern alternatives.\n\u2022 Solid-State Drives (SSD): A newer
        type of storage that uses flash memory with no moving parts. SSDs are faster,
        quieter, and more durable than HDDs, making them ideal for high-performance
        computing.\n\u2022 Flash Drives (USB Drives): Portable, small storage devices
        that connect through USB ports. They are convenient for transferring files
        between computers.\n\u2022 Memory Cards: Compact storage used in devices
        like cameras, smartphones, and tablets. Common types include SD cards and
        microSD cards.\n\u2022 External Hard Drives: Portable versions of HDDs or
        SSDs that connect to computers via USB or other ports, offering extra storage
        or backup options.\n\nStorage devices make it possible to save everything
        from text documents to videos, photos, and complex applications. As technology
        advances, storage has become faster, more compact, and capable of holding
        vast amounts of data, empowering users to store their digital lives securely
        and efficiently."
      objectReference: {fileID: 0}
    - target: {fileID: 5999933893511949893, guid: a01cfc34c5d09034dbd62d1a7d2cc505,
        type: 3}
      propertyPath: infoText
      value: 'Storage Devices

        Click "F'' To Study'
      objectReference: {fileID: 0}
    - target: {fileID: 5999933893511949893, guid: a01cfc34c5d09034dbd62d1a7d2cc505,
        type: 3}
      propertyPath: id
      value: Storage Devices
      objectReference: {fileID: 0}
    - target: {fileID: 5999933893511949893, guid: a01cfc34c5d09034dbd62d1a7d2cc505,
        type: 3}
      propertyPath: activateDistance
      value: 2.99
      objectReference: {fileID: 0}
    - target: {fileID: 5999933893511949893, guid: a01cfc34c5d09034dbd62d1a7d2cc505,
        type: 3}
      propertyPath: Content
      value: "Storage devices are critical components of modern computer systems.
        They serve the essential function of holding and preserving digital information
        for both short-term and long-term use. While input devices allow users to
        send data into a computer and output devices display the results, storage
        devices ensure that the data and programs we use are safely saved for future
        access, even after the computer is turned off.\n\nUnlike volatile memory,
        such as RAM, which temporarily holds data during active use, storage devices
        are non-volatile, meaning they retain information even when the system is
        powered down. This distinction is vital for keeping files, software, and
        system settings intact over time.\n\nSeveral types of storage devices exist,
        each with unique characteristics and uses:\n\u2022 Hard Disk Drives (HDD):
        Traditional storage devices that use spinning magnetic disks to store data.
        HDDs provide large storage capacity at a relatively low cost but are slower
        than some modern alternatives.\n\u2022 Solid-State Drives (SSD): A newer
        type of storage that uses flash memory with no moving parts. SSDs are faster,
        quieter, and more durable than HDDs, making them ideal for high-performance
        computing.\n\u2022 Flash Drives (USB Drives): Portable, small storage devices
        that connect through USB ports. They are convenient for transferring files
        between computers.\n\u2022 Memory Cards: Compact storage used in devices
        like cameras, smartphones, and tablets. Common types include SD cards and
        microSD cards.\n\u2022 External Hard Drives: Portable versions of HDDs or
        SSDs that connect to computers via USB or other ports, offering extra storage
        or backup options.\n\nStorage devices make it possible to save everything
        from text documents to videos, photos, and complex applications. As technology
        advances, storage has become faster, more compact, and capable of holding
        vast amounts of data, empowering users to store their digital lives securely
        and efficiently."
      objectReference: {fileID: 0}
