    - target: {fileID: 5502387711208104083, guid: a01cfc34c5d09034dbd62d1a7d2cc505,
        type: 3}
      propertyPath: m_Text
      value: 'Random Access Memory (RAM) is a vital component in every computer system,
        responsible for temporarily holding data and instructions that the computer
        is actively using. Unlike permanent storage, RAM is volatile, meaning its
        contents are erased when the computer is powered off or restarted.


        RAM
        serves as the workspace for the CPU, allowing it to access necessary data
        quickly without constantly retrieving it from slower storage devices. This
        enables smoother, faster performance when running applications, loading files,
        and multitasking.


        When a user opens a program or file, it is loaded
        from storage (such as an HDD or SSD) into RAM. The CPU can then access this
        information rapidly, resulting in quick response times and efficient operation.
        The more RAM a computer has, the more applications and processes it can handle
        simultaneously without slowing down.


        RAM comes in different sizes
        and speeds, with modern computers typically having several gigabytes of RAM.
        Upgrading RAM is one of the most effective ways to improve a computer''s
        performance, especially for resource-intensive tasks like gaming, video editing,
        or running multiple programs at once.


        Despite its importance, RAM
        does not retain information permanently. Once the system shuts down, all
        data stored in RAM is cleared, highlighting its role as temporary working
        memory.'
      objectReference: {fileID: 0}
    - target: {fileID: 5999933893511949893, guid: a01cfc34c5d09034dbd62d1a7d2cc505,
        type: 3}
      propertyPath: infoText
      value: 'Understanding RAM (Random Access Memory)

        Click "F'' To Study'
      objectReference: {fileID: 0}
    - target: {fileID: 5999933893511949893, guid: a01cfc34c5d09034dbd62d1a7d2cc505,
        type: 3}
      propertyPath: id
      value: Understanding RAM (Random Access Memory)
      objectReference: {fileID: 0}
    - target: {fileID: 5999933893511949893, guid: a01cfc34c5d09034dbd62d1a7d2cc505,
        type: 3}
      propertyPath: activateDistance
      value: 2.45
      objectReference: {fileID: 0}
    - target: {fileID: 5999933893511949893, guid: a01cfc34c5d09034dbd62d1a7d2cc505,
        type: 3}
      propertyPath: Content
      value: 'Random Access Memory (RAM) is a vital component in every computer system,
        responsible for temporarily holding data and instructions that the computer
        is actively using. Unlike permanent storage, RAM is volatile, meaning its
        contents are erased when the computer is powered off or restarted.


        RAM
        serves as the workspace for the CPU, allowing it to access necessary data
        quickly without constantly retrieving it from slower storage devices. This
        enables smoother, faster performance when running applications, loading files,
        and multitasking.


        When a user opens a program or file, it is loaded
        from storage (such as an HDD or SSD) into RAM. The CPU can then access this
        information rapidly, resulting in quick response times and efficient operation.
        The more RAM a computer has, the more applications and processes it can handle
        simultaneously without slowing down.


        RAM comes in different sizes
        and speeds, with modern computers typically having several gigabytes of RAM.
        Upgrading RAM is one of the most effective ways to improve a computer''s
        performance, especially for resource-intensive tasks like gaming, video editing,
        or running multiple programs at once.


        Despite its importance, RAM
        does not retain information permanently. Once the system shuts down, all
