    - target: {fileID: 5502387711208104083, guid: a01cfc34c5d09034dbd62d1a7d2cc505,
        type: 3}
      propertyPath: m_Text
      value: "The Central Processing Unit, commonly referred to as the CPU, is often
        called the \"brain\" of the computer\u2014and with good reason. It is the
        primary component responsible for executing instructions, performing calculations,
        and processing data. Every action that a computer takes, from simple tasks
        like opening a folder to complex operations such as running video games or
        scientific simulations, relies on the CPU.\n\nThe CPU interprets and carries
        out commands given by both the user and the software running on the system.
        It operates in close coordination with other computer components, especially
        RAM (Random Access Memory), which temporarily holds the data and instructions
        the CPU needs quick access to.\n\nModern CPUs are made up of multiple cores,
        each capable of processing its own set of instructions. This allows for multitasking
        and faster performance. Additionally, CPUs operate at high speeds, measured
        in gigahertz (GHz), which determines how quickly they can execute instructions.\n\nWithout
        the CPU, a computer would be unable to perform even the most basic operations.
        It manages and coordinates the entire system, ensuring that input is received,
        processes are executed, and output is produced efficiently.\n\nAs technology
        has evolved, CPUs have become smaller, faster, and more powerful, enabling
        computers to perform increasingly complex tasks with ease."
      objectReference: {fileID: 0}
    - target: {fileID: 5999933893511949893, guid: a01cfc34c5d09034dbd62d1a7d2cc505,
        type: 3}
      propertyPath: infoText
      value: 'The Central Processing Unit (CPU)

        Click "F'' To Study'
      objectReference: {fileID: 0}
    - target: {fileID: 5999933893511949893, guid: a01cfc34c5d09034dbd62d1a7d2cc505,
        type: 3}
      propertyPath: id
      value: The Central Processing Unit (CPU)
      objectReference: {fileID: 0}
    - target: {fileID: 5999933893511949893, guid: a01cfc34c5d09034dbd62d1a7d2cc505,
        type: 3}
      propertyPath: activateDistance
      value: 2.72
      objectReference: {fileID: 0}
    - target: {fileID: 5999933893511949893, guid: a01cfc34c5d09034dbd62d1a7d2cc505,
        type: 3}
      propertyPath: Content
      value: "The Central Processing Unit, commonly referred to as the CPU, is often
        called the \"brain\" of the computer\u2014and with good reason. It is the
        primary component responsible for executing instructions, performing calculations,
        and processing data. Every action that a computer takes, from simple tasks
        like opening a folder to complex operations such as running video games or
        scientific simulations, relies on the CPU.\n\nThe CPU interprets and carries
        out commands given by both the user and the software running on the system.
        It operates in close coordination with other computer components, especially
        RAM (Random Access Memory), which temporarily holds the data and instructions
        the CPU needs quick access to.\n\nModern CPUs are made up of multiple cores,
        each capable of processing its own set of instructions. This allows for multitasking
        and faster performance. Additionally, CPUs operate at high speeds, measured
        in gigahertz (GHz), which determines how quickly they can execute instructions.\n\nWithout
        the CPU, a computer would be unable to perform even the most basic operations.
        It manages and coordinates the entire system, ensuring that input is received,
        processes are executed, and output is produced efficiently.\n\nAs technology
        has evolved, CPUs have become smaller, faster, and more powerful, enabling
        computers to perform increasingly complex tasks with ease."
      objectReference: {fileID: 0}
